# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: decentralized-identity-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] A **decentralized identifier (DID)** is a type of globally unique identifier that enables an entity to be identified in a manner that is verifiable, persistent (as long as the DID controller desires), and does not require the use of a centralized registry.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] DIDs enable a new model of decentralized digital identity that is often referred to as a self-sovereign identity (SSI).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The DIDs are an important component of decentralized web applications.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] A decentralized identifier resolves (points) to a **DID document**, a set of data describing the DID subject, including mechanisms, such as cryptographic public keys, that the DID subject or a DID delegate can use to authenticate itself and prove its association with the DID.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Just as there are many different types of URIs, all of which conform to the URI standard, there are many different types of **DID methods**, all of which must conform to the DID standard.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group maintains a registry of DID methods.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] A DID identifies any subject (e.g., a person, organization, thing, data model, abstract entity, etc.) that the controller of the DID decides that it identifies.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are designed to enable the controller of a DID to prove control over it and to be implemented independently of any centralized registry, identity provider, or certificate authority.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are URIs that associate a DID subject with a DID document.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Each DID document can express cryptographic material, verification methods, and service endpoints to enable trusted interactions associated with the DID subject.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might contain additional semantics about the subject that it identifies.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might also contain the DID subject itself (e.g. a data model).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] National efforts include the European Digital Identity (EUDI) Wallet as a part of eIDAS 2.0 in the European Union, and China Real-Name Decentralized Identifier System (China RealDID) under China's Ministry of Public Security.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The AT Protocol and applications powered by the protocol such as Bluesky use DIDs for their identity system in order to give users full control over their identity, including where their data is stored.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The protocol uses its own DID method, did:plc, as well as a general domain-based method with did:web.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Persona is an identity verification company founded in 2018.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Its product consists of uploading a government-issued ID and potentially taking a selfie to confirm the user's identity and give them a DID identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The service is used by the LinkedIn professional networking site, the Discord and Reddit social media networks, the Roblox video game platform, and the OpenAI artificial intelligence company.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is a privacy-focused digital identity solution developed by Polygon, a blockchain scaling platform.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] It leverages zero-knowledge proofs (ZKPs) to allow users to verify specific aspects of their identity—such as age or residency—without revealing underlying personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] This enables secure and private interactions with services that require identity verification, such as financial platforms, voting systems, or DAO governance, while preserving user anonymity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is already being explored by governments and organizations seeking compliant and privacy-preserving identity systems in Web3 environments.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group developed a specification for decentralized identifiers to standardize the core architecture, data model, and representation of DIDs.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The W3C approved the DID 1.0 specification as a W3C Recommendation on July 19, 2022.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/decentralized-identifier] The Decentralized Identity Foundation (DIF) published a Dynamic Traveler Profile Generation Specification in June 2023, for use cases in the travel industry.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A **digital identity** is data stored on computer systems relating to an individual, organization, application, or device.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] For individuals, it involves the collection of personal data that is essential for facilitating automated access to digital services, confirming one's identity on the internet, and allowing digital systems to manage interactions between different parties.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] It is a component of a person's social identity in the digital realm, often referred to as their online identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identities are composed of the full range of data produced by a person's activities on the internet, which may include usernames and passwords, search histories, dates of birth, social security numbers, and records of online purchases.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] When such personal information is accessible in the public domain, it can be used by others to piece together a person's offline identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Furthermore, this information can be compiled to construct a data double, a comprehensive profile created from a person's scattered digital footprints across various platforms.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] These profiles enable personalized experiences on the internet and within different digital services.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A critical problem in cyberspace is knowing who one is interacting with.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Using only static identifiers such as passwords and email, there is no way to precisely determine the identity of a person in cyberspace because this information can be stolen or used by many individuals acting as one.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identity based on dynamic entity relationships captured from behavioral history across multiple websites and mobile apps can verify and authenticate identity with up to 95% accuracy.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] By comparing a set of entity relationships between a new event (e.g., login) and past events, a pattern of convergence can verify or authenticate the identity as legitimate whereas divergence indicates an attempt to mask an identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Data used for digital identity is generally encrypted using a one-way hash, thereby avoiding privacy concerns.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Because it is based on behavioral history, a digital identity is very hard to fake or steal.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A digital identity may also be referred to as a *digital subject* or *digital entity*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] They are the digital representation of a set of claims made by one party about itself or another person, group, thing, or concept.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A digital twin which is also commonly known as a data double or virtual twin is a secondary version of the original user's data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Which is used both as a way to observe what said user does on the internet as well as customize a more personalized internet experience.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Due to the collection of personal data, there have been many social, political, and legal controversies tying into data doubles.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] While in manufacturing and other multi-organization environments, digital identity is used to enable secure interactions between separate organizations.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] For a secure federated digital thread, participating systems rely on verified digital identities to authenticate organizations before exchanging product lifecycle data, supporting trust and controlled data sharing across organizational boundaries.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The attributes of a digital identity are acquired and contain information about a user, such as medical history, purchasing behavior, bank balance, age, and so on.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Preferences retain a user's choices such as favorite brand of shoes, and preferred currency.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Traits are features of the user that are inherent, such as eye color, nationality, and place of birth.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Although attributes of a user can change easily, traits change slowly, if at all.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A digital identity also has entity relationships derived from the devices, environment, and locations from which an individual is active on the Internet.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Some of those include facial recognition, fingerprints, photos, and so many more personal attributes/preferences.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identities can be issued through digital certificates.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] These certificates contain data associated with a user and are issued with legal guarantees by recognized certification authorities.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] In order to assign a digital representation to an entity, the attributing party must trust that the claim of an attribute (such as name, location, role as an employee, or age) is correct and associated with the person or thing presenting the attribute.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Conversely, the individual claiming an attribute may only grant selective access to its information (e.g., proving identity in a bar or PayPal authentication for payment at a website).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] In this way, digital identity is better understood as a particular viewpoint within a mutually-agreed relationship than as an objective property.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Physical authentication techniques include iris scanning, fingerprinting, and voice recognition; those techniques are called *biometrics*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The use of both static identifiers (e.g., username and password) and personal unique attributes (e.g., biometrics) is called *multi-factor authentication* and is more secure than the use of one component alone.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Whilst technological progress in authentication continues to evolve, these systems do not prevent aliases from being used.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] To address this, proof of personhood protocols such as World ID by Tool for Humanity, Humanode, and BrightID are increasingly employed to verify that a digital identity belongs to a unique, living human, effectively preventing the creation of duplicate accounts or automated Sybil identities.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] In blockchain systems, account-based identity approaches include ERC-725, a draft Ethereum standard for smart-contract accounts with generic data storage and execution, and LUKSO Universal Profiles, which use ERC-725/LSP0 to combine profile metadata with account permissions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The introduction of strong authentication for online payment transactions within the European Union now links a verified person to an account, where such person has been identified in accordance with statutory requirements prior to account being opened.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Verifying a person opening an account online typically requires a form of device binding to the credentials being used.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This verifies that the device that stands in for a person on the Internet is actually the individual's device and not the device of someone simply claiming to be the individual.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The concept of reliance authentication makes use of pre-existing accounts, to piggy back further services upon those accounts, providing that the original source is reliable.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] An example of reliance authentication is PayPal's verification method.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Consider the person who rents a car and checks into a hotel with a credit card.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The car rental and hotel company may request authentication that there is credit enough for an accident, or profligate spending on room service.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Thus a card may later be refused when trying to purchase an activity such as a balloon trip.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Though there is adequate credit to pay for the rental, the hotel, and the balloon trip, there is an insufficient amount to also cover the authorizations.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The actual charges are authorized after leaving the hotel and returning the car, which may be too late for the balloon trip.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Valid online authorization requires analysis of information related to the digital event including device and environmental variables.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] These are generally derived from the data exchanged between a device and a business server over the Internet.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Businesses use identity verification services to check whether a person has provided information associated with the identity of a real person.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This is a form of electronic authentication.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Some websites with user accounts, such as social media services, offer account verification to show that an account is operated by a specific person.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Some decentralized identity verification systems, such as within the Fediverse and Mastodon, use a web standard microformat called `rel="me"`.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The `rel="me"` value is an HTML link relationship attribute used to indicate that two web resources represent the same person or entity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] It originated as part of early web microformats and has been used in decentralized identity systems to associate profiles and websites controlled by a single individual.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identity requires digital identifiers—strings or tokens that are unique within a given scope (globally or locally within a specific domain, community, directory, application, etc.).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Identifiers may be classified as *omnidirectional* or *unidirectional*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Omnidirectional identifiers are public and easily discoverable, whereas unidirectional identifiers are intended to be private and used only in the context of a specific identity relationship.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Identifiers may also be classified as *resolvable* or *non-resolvable*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Resolvable identifiers, such as a domain name or email address, may be easily dereferenced into the entity they represent, or some current state data providing relevant attributes of that entity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Non-resolvable identifiers, such as a person's real name, or the name of a subject or topic, can be compared for equivalence but are not otherwise machine-understandable.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] There are many different schemes and formats for digital identifiers.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) and the internationalized version Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) are the standard for identifiers for websites on the World Wide Web.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] OpenID and Light-weight Identity are two web authentication protocols that use standard HTTP URIs (often called URLs).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A Uniform Resource Name is a persistent, location-independent identifier assigned within the defined namespace.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital object architecture is a means of managing digital information in a network environment.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] In digital object architecture, a digital object has a machine and platform independent structure that allows it to be identified, accessed and protected, as appropriate.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A digital object may incorporate not only informational elements, i.e., a digitized version of a paper, movie or sound recording, but also the unique identifier of the digital object and other metadata about the digital object.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The metadata may include restrictions on access to digital objects, notices of ownership, and identifiers for licensing agreements, if appropriate.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The Handle System is a general purpose distributed information system that provides efficient, extensible, and secure identifier and resolution services for use on networks such as the internet.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] It includes an open set of protocols, a namespace, and a reference implementation of the protocols.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The protocols enable a distributed computer system to store identifiers, known as handles, of arbitrary resources and resolve those handles into the information necessary to locate, access, contact, authenticate, or otherwise make use of the resources.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This information can be changed as needed to reflect the current state of the identified resource without changing its identifier, thus allowing the name of the item to persist over changes of location and other related state information.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The original version of the Handle System technology was developed with support from the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A new OASIS standard for abstract, structured identifiers, XRI (Extensible Resource Identifiers), adds new features to URIs and IRIs that are especially useful for digital identity systems.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] OpenID also supports XRIs, which are the basis for i-names.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Analysis are performed based on quantifiable metrics, such as transaction velocity, locale settings (or attempts to obfuscate), and user-input data (such as ship-to address).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Correlation and deviation are mapped to tolerances and scored, then aggregated across multiple entities to compute a transaction risk-score, which assess the risk posed to an organization.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identity attributes exist within the context of ontologies.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The development of digital identity network solutions that can interoperate taxonomically diverse representations of digital identity is a contemporary challenge.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Free-tagging has emerged recently as an effective way of circumventing this challenge (to date, primarily with application to the identity of digital entities such as bookmarks and photos) by effectively flattening identity attributes into a single, unstructured layer.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] However, the organic integration of the benefits of both structured and fluid approaches to identity attribute management remains elusive.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Identity relationships within a digital network may include multiple identity entities.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] And if identity relationships are to reach beyond the context of a single, federated ontology of identity (see Taxonomies of identity above), identity attributes must somehow be matched across diverse ontologies.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The development of network approaches that can embody such integrated "compound" trust relationships is currently a topic of much debate in the blogosphere.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Integrated compound trust relationships allow, for example, entity A to accept an assertion or claim about entity B by entity C.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] C thus vouches for an aspect of B's identity to A.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A key feature of "compound" trust relationships is the possibility of selective disclosure from one entity to another of locally relevant information.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] As an illustration of the potential application of selective disclosure, let us suppose a certain Diana wished to book a hire car without disclosing irrelevant personal information (using a notional digital identity network that supports compound trust relationships).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] As an adult, UK resident with a current driving license, Diana might have the UK's Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency vouch for her driving qualification, age, and nationality to a car-rental company without having her name or contact details disclosed.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Similarly, Diana's bank might assert just her banking details to the rental company.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Selective disclosure allows for appropriate privacy of information within a network of identity relationships.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A classic form of networked digital identity based on international standards is the "White Pages".
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] An electronic white pages links various devices, like computers and telephones, to an individual or organization.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Various attributes such as X.509v3 digital certificates for secure cryptographic communications are captured under a schema, and published in an LDAP or X.500 directory.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Changes to the LDAP standard are managed by working groups in the IETF, and changes in X.500 are managed by the ISO.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The ITU did significant analysis of gaps in digital identity interoperability via the FGidm (ƒfocus group on identity management).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Implementations of X.500[2005] and LDAPv3 have occurred worldwide but are primarily located in major data centers with administrative policy boundaries regarding sharing of personal information.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Since combined X.500 [2005] and LDAPv3 directories can hold millions of unique objects for rapid access, it is expected to play a continued role for large scale secure identity access services.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] LDAPv3 can act as a lightweight standalone server, or in the original design as a TCP-IP based Lightweight Directory Access Protocol compatible with making queries to an X.500 mesh of servers which can run the native OSI protocol.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The ability to leverage and extend a networked digital identity is made more practicable by the expression of the level of trust associated with the given identity through a common Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] In digital rhetoric, digital identity is treated as a rhetorical construction shaped by the choices users make in how they represent themselves online, rather than as a fixed attribute of a person.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Researchers in the field study how those self-representations are influenced by platform design, audience, and the technical affordances available for self-presentation.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Sherry Turkle, in *Life on the Screen* (1995), argued that online environments allow users to present multiple, fluid versions of the self that are less anchored to physical embodiment than offline identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Later scholarship has questioned how far this separation extends in practice, arguing that characteristics such as race, gender, and class continue to shape how users are perceived and treated online.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Clare Sullivan presents the grounds for digital identity as an emerging legal concept.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The UK's Identity Cards Act 2006 confirms Sullivan's argument and unfolds the new legal concept involving database identity and transaction identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Database identity is the collection of data that is registered about an individual within the databases of the scheme and transaction identity is a set of information that defines the individual's identity for transactional purposes.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Although there is reliance on the verification of identity, none of the processes used are entirely trustworthy.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The consequences of digital identity abuse and fraud are potentially serious since in possible implications the person is held legally responsible.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Legal scholars Lusine Vardanyan, Ondrej Hamulak, and Hovsep Kocharyan from Palacký University in Olomouc have analyzed the complexities of digital identity and its regulation.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Their research highlights the difficulties that current legal frameworks face in adequately safeguarding digital identity against manipulation, unauthorized use, and opaque profiling mechanisms.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] They argue that existing data protection regimes predominantly focus on the protection of information rather than the individual as a whole, which may contribute to a loss of control over one's digital presence.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] A key concept proposed to address these issues is the right to informational self-determination, which would provide individuals with greater control over the collection, use, and dissemination of their personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This right is seen as essential in ensuring personal autonomy, enabling individuals to shape and manage their digital identities in alignment with their real-world personas.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Proponents argue that the development of legal tools for digital identity management should be grounded in principles such as informed consent, transparency, and self-governance.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] The work of scholars such as Shoshana Zuboff has been influential in highlighting the risks associated with the commodification of personal data and the erosion of individual agency in digital spaces.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Recognizing informational self-determination as a fundamental right is viewed as a critical step in enhancing data protection and ensuring security and autonomy in an increasingly networked society.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Corporations are recognizing the power of the internet to tailor their online presence to each individual customer.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Purchase suggestions, personalized adverts, and other tailored marketing strategies are a great success for businesses.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Such tailoring, however, depends on the ability to connect attributes and preferences to the identity of the visitor.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] As the internet becomes more attuned to privacy concerns, media publishers, application developers, and online retailers are re-evaluating their strategies, sometimes reinventing their business models completely.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Increasingly, the trend is shifting towards monetizing online offerings directly, with users being asked to pay for access through subscriptions and other forms of payment, moving away from the reliance on collecting personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital death is the phenomenon of people continuing to have Internet accounts after their deaths.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This results in several ethical issues concerning how the information stored by the deceased person may be used or stored or given to the family members.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] It also may result in confusion due to automated social media features such as birthday reminders, as well as uncertainty about the deceased person's willingness to pass their personal information to a third party.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Many social media platforms do not have clear policies about digital death.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Many companies secure digital identities after death or legally pass those on to the deceased people's families.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Some companies will also provide options for digital identity erasure after death.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Facebook/Meta is a clear-cut example of a company that provides digital options after death.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Descendants or friends of the deceased individual can let Facebook know about the death and have all of their previous digital activity removed.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital activity is but not limited to messages, photos, posts, comments, reactions, stories, archived history, etc.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Furthermore, the entire Facebook account will be deleted upon request.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] There are proponents of treating self-determination and freedom of expression of digital identity as a new human right.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Some have speculated that digital identities could become a new form of legal entity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] As technology develops so does the intelligence of certain digital identities, moving forward many believe that there should be more developments in legal aspects that regulate online presences and collection.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identity can be a component to techno-authoritarianism.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] GDPR is one attempt to address this concern using the regulation.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] This regulation tactic was introduced by the European Union (EU) in 2018 for addressing concerns about the privacy and personal data of EU citizens.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] GDPR applies to all companies, regardless of location, that handle users within the EU.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Any company that collects, stores, and operates with data from EU citizens must disclose key details about the management of that data to EU individuals.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] EU citizens can also request for certain aspects of their collected data to be deleted.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Many systems provide privacy-related mitigations when analyzing data linked to digital identities.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] One common mitigation is data anonymization, such as hashing user identifiers with a cryptographic hash function.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Another popular technique is adding statistical noise to a data set to reduce identifiability, such as in differential privacy.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Although a digital identity allows consumers to transact from anywhere and more easily manage various ID cards, it also poses a potential single point of compromise that malicious hackers can use to steal all of that personal information.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Hence, several different account authentication methods have been created to protect users.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Initially, these authentication methods will require a setup from the user to enable these security features when attempting a login.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Although many facets of digital identity are universal owing in part to the ubiquity of the Internet, some regional variations exist due to specific laws, practices, and government services that are in place.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] For example, digital identity can use services that validate driving licences, passports, and other physical documents online to help improve the quality of a digital identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Also, strict policies against money laundering mean that some services, such as money transfers, need a stricter level of validation of digital identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/digital-identity] Digital identity in the national sense can mean a combination of single sign-on and/or validation of assertions by trusted authorities (generally the government).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] A **distributed ledger** (also called a **shared ledger** or **distributed ledger technology** or **DLT**) is a system whereby replicated, shared, and synchronized digital data is geographically spread (distributed) across many sites, countries, or institutions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] In contrast to a centralized database, a distributed ledger does not require a central administrator, and consequently does not have a single (central) point-of-failure.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] In general, a distributed ledger requires a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network and consensus algorithms so that the ledger is reliably replicated across distributed computer nodes (servers, clients, etc.).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] The most common form of distributed ledger technology is the blockchain (commonly associated with cryptocurrency), which can either be on a public or private network.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Infrastructure for data management is a common barrier to implementing DLT.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Distributed ledger data is typically spread across multiple nodes (computational devices) on a P2P network, where each replicates and saves an identical copy of the ledger data and updates itself independently of other nodes.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] The primary advantage of this distributed processing pattern is the lack of a central authority, which would constitute a single point of failure.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] When a ledger update transaction is broadcast to the P2P network, each distributed node processes a new update transaction independently, and then collectively all working nodes use a consensus algorithm to determine the correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Once a consensus has been determined, all the other nodes update themselves with the latest, correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Security is enforced through cryptographic keys and signatures.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Certificate Transparency is an Internet security standard for monitoring and auditing the issuance of digital certificates based on a distributed ledger.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] It was initiated in 2011, standardised in 2013 and started to be used by the Google Chrome browser for all certificates in 2018.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] In 2016, some banks tested distributed ledger systems for payments to determine their usefulness.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] In 2020, Axoni launched Veris, a distributed ledger platform that manages equity swap transactions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] The platform, which matches and reconciles post-trade data on stock swaps, is used by BlackRock Inc., Goldman Sachs Group Inc., and Citigroup, Inc.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] A pilot scheme by the Monetary Authority of Singapore completed its first live trades using DLT in 2022.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] The pilot by Singapore's central bank involved JP Morgan, SBI Digital Asset Holdings and DBS.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] The banks traded using smart contracts against liquidity pools of tokenized Singapore government bonds, Japanese government bonds, yen, and Singapore dollars.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Standard Chartered Bank is exploring tokens for trade finance; and HSBC and United Overseas Bank are working with Marketnode, a digital markets infrastructure provider, on products for wealth management.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLT can be used for smart contracting, which is the formation of contracts which automatically complete when triggered by prevailing conditions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLT is itself secured by cryptographic methods, but can also be used as a base layer on which to build further cryptographic applications, such as protocols that require or benefit from a public broadcast mechanism, including transparent decryption.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] In the context of cryptocurrencies, distributed ledger technologies can be categorized in terms of their data structures, consensus algorithms, permissions, and whether they are mined.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLT data structure types include linear data structures (blockchains) to more complex directed acyclic graph (DAG) and hybrid data structures.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLT consensus algorithm types include proof-of-work (PoW) and proof-of-stake (PoS) algorithms and DAG consensus-building and voting algorithms.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLTs are generally either permissioned (private) or permissionless (public).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] PoW cryptocurrencies are generally either 'mined' or 'non-mined', where the latter typically indicates 'pre-mined' cryptocurrencies, such as XRP or IOTA.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] PoS cryptocurrencies do not use miners, instead usually relying on validation among owners of the cryptocurrency, such as Cardano or Solana.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Blockchains are the most common DLT type, with a 256-bit secure hash algorithm (SHA).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] DLTs based on DAG data structures or hybrid blockchain-DAG decrease transaction data size and transaction costs, while increasing transaction speeds compared with bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Examples of DAG DLT cryptocurrencies include MIOTA (IOTA Tangle DLT) and HBAR (Hedera Hashgraph).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/distributed-ledger] Holochain represents a departure from traditional DLT models, using an agent-centric approach with individual source chains and a distributed hash table (DHT) for data validation, eliminating the need for a global consensus mechanism.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The TCP/IP protocol provides identifiers for machines, but not for the people and organisations operating the machines.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Services provide identifiers for the user, not the network.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The absence of reliable identifiers is one of the primary sources of cybercrime, fraud, and threats to privacy on the internet.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] With the advent of blockchain technology, a new model for decentralized identity emerged in 2015.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The FIDO Alliance proposed an identity model that was no longer account-based, but identified people through direct, private, peer-to-peer connections secured by public/private key cryptography.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Self-Sovereign Identity (SSI) summarises all components of the decentralized identity model: digital wallets, digital credentials, and digital connections.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] SSI addresses the difficulty of establishing trust in an interaction.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] In order to be trusted, one party in an interaction will present credentials to the other parties, and those relying on the parties can verify that the credentials came from an issuer that they trust.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] In this way, the verifier's trust in the issuer is transferred to the credential holder.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] This basic structure of SSI with three participants is sometimes called "the trust triangle".
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] It is generally recognized that for an identity system to be self-sovereign, users control the verifiable credentials that they hold, and their consent is required to use those credentials.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] This reduces the unintended sharing of users' personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] This is contrasted with the centralized identity paradigm where identity is provided by some outside entity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] In an SSI system, holders generate and control unique identifiers called decentralized identifiers.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Most SSI systems are decentralized, where the credentials are managed using crypto wallets and verified using public-key cryptography anchored on a distributed ledger.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The credentials may contain data from an issuer's database, a social media account, a history of transactions on an e-commerce site, or attestation from friends or colleagues.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Some blockchain identity systems use smart contracts as accounts with attachable data and permissions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] ERC-725 is a draft Ethereum standard for smart-contract accounts with generic data storage and execution.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] LUKSO's Universal Profiles apply this model to on-chain profiles, combining a recoverable smart-contract account with public profile data for decentralized applications.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The European Union is exploring decentralized digital identity through a number of initiatives including the International Association for Trusted Blockchain Application (INATBA), the EU Blockchain Observatory & Forum and the European SSI Framework.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] In 2019, the EU created an eIDAS compatible European Self-Sovereign Identity Framework (ESSIF).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The ESSIF makes use of decentralized identifiers (DIDs) and the European Blockchain Services Infrastructure (EBSI).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The Korean government created a public/private consortium specifically for decentralized identity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] In the German and European legal area, there are two regulations that are of particular importance for the topic.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] These include the eIDAS Regulation, which forms the most important framework for trust in electronic identification in the EU and is a fundamental building block of the digital single market.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The European Blockchain Service Infrastructure (EBSI) has provided the SSI eIDAS Bridge, as a technical implementation that enables a substantial level of trust.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The eIDAS SSI legal report also describes several scenarios of how SSI can fulfill the necessary regulatory conditions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Furthermore, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) forms the legal basis for the handling of personal data.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The EBSI GDPR Legal Report provides more information on this.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] SSI is a value laden technology whose technical operationalizations differ (see Technical aspects).
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Therefore, its implementations can vary significantly and embed into the very technology different goals, agenda, and intentions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The term "self-sovereign identity" can create expectations that individuals have absolute control and ownership over their digital identities, akin to physical possessions.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] However, in practice, SSI involves complex technical infrastructure, interactions with identity issuers and verifiers, and compliance with legal frameworks.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] The reality may not align with the perception generated by the term, leading to semantic confusion.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Critics argue that SSI may exacerbate social inequalities and exclude those with limited access to technology or digital literacy.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] SSI assumes reliable internet connectivity, access to compatible devices, and proficiency in navigating digital systems.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/self-sovereign-identity] Consequently, marginalized populations, including the elderly, individuals in developing regions, or those with limited technological resources, may face exclusion and reduced access to the benefits of SSI.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials can be issued by anyone, about anything, and can be presented to and verified by everyone.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The entity that generates the credential is called the *Issuer*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The credential is then given to the *Holder* who stores it for later use.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The Holder can then prove something about themselves by presenting their credentials to a *Verifier*.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a verifiable credential operates in a triangle of trust, mediating between issuer and verifier.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Any role in the triangle can be played by a person, an institution, or a machine.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Note that because verifiable credentials can be created by anyone, the verifier decides if they trust the issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The VC model places the holder of a credential at the center of the identity ecosystem, giving individuals control of their identity attributes.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The W3C VC model parallels physical credentials: the user holds cards and can present them to anyone at any time without informing or requiring the permission of the card issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Such a model is decentralized and gives much more autonomy and privacy to the participants.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] This contrasts with the federated identity management (FIM) model, as adopted by SAML and OpenID Connect, which place the identity provider (IdP) in the central role as the dispenser of identity attributes and the determiner of which Service Providers (SPs) it will give them to.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] In the federated model, the IdP knows every SP that the user visits.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The data model for verifiable credentials is a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Recommendation, "Verifiable Credentials Data Model 1.0 - Expressing verifiable information on the Web", published 19 November 2019.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The VC context, defined using the `@context` JSON property, is a JSON-LD construct that allows user friendly terms to be used for JSON properties.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] According to the VC data model, the value of many properties must be a URI.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Whilst these are globally unambiguous, (important for a global data model), they are not user-friendly.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Consequently, the `@context` property allows short-form, user-friendly aliases to be defined for each URI.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] This makes it much easier, and more user-friendly, to specify VCs.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Any new property can be added to VCs, as determined by the issuer.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Standard properties have been defined specifically as extension points.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a VC does not always have to be the subject of the credential.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] It is expected that most users will hold their own VCs, i.e., the holder and the subject will be the same entity.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] For example, when the VC subject is an infant, and the VC is a birth certificate, the holder may be one or both parents.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] No proof mechanism is standardized but the data model is flexible enough to support various existing cryptographic mechanisms, such as digital signatures.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Proof mechanisms that are in use include: JSON Web Tokens with JSON Web Signatures, JSON-LD proofs, and zero-knowledge proofs using schemes such as IBM's anonymous credentials.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Various protocols are specified for carrying VCs from the issuer/IdP to the holder, and the holder to the verifier.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] None of these protocols has become standardized.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Many people who are experimenting with VCs use HTTPS to carry VCs between the various parties.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] The security of verifiable credentials in the context of COVID-19 vaccination and test certificates has been questioned.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials have also been subject to usability concerns.
[src:decentralized-identity-deep/verifiable-credentials] Some have likened anyone being able to issue a verifiable credential being like a shop clerk deciding if they should accept an out-of-state license as proof of age when purchasing alcohol.
